---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Text from "@/components/fundations/elements/Text.astro";
import Wrapper from "@/components/fundations/containers/Wrapper.astro";
import DocWithToc from "@/components/global/DocWithToc.astro";
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Collective Charter"
  description="The governing charter for the UI Collective, covering purpose, membership, conduct, governance, and dispute resolution."
  pageType="webpage"
>
  <section>
    <Wrapper variant="standard" class="py-12">
      <DocWithToc tocId="collective-charter" tocMinLevel={2} tocMaxLevel={2}>
        <Text
          slot="hero"
          tag="h1"
          variant="textBase"
          class="text-foreground font-medium text-balance"
        >
          Collective Charter
        </Text>
        <p>
          <a href="https://uicollective.org/">uicollective.org</a>
        </p>

        <h2>Preamble</h2>
        <p>
          The UI Collective is a professional association of independent template
          and UI creators who build and sell production-quality templates, UI kits,
          component libraries, and design systems. We are practitioners, founders,
          and full-time operators in this space — united by a shared commitment to
          quality, integrity, and the long-term health of our industry.
        </p>
        <p>
          Membership in the Collective is a public signal: that you are a known,
          trusted creator who upholds ethical standards, respects intellectual
          property, and conducts business in good faith.
        </p>

        <h2>Article I — Purpose</h2>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Professional Standards.</strong> Establish and uphold shared
            standards of quality, ethics, and professionalism for commercial
            template and UI creation.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Industry Integrity.</strong> Identify, discuss, and address
            problematic behaviors that harm creators, customers, and the broader
            ecosystem — including plagiarism, license violations, deceptive
            marketing, and systematic IP theft.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Credible Membership.</strong> Maintain a membership process
            that is meaningful — so that being a member of the Collective carries
            weight as a mark of professionalism and good standing.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Mutual Support.</strong> Foster a trusted space for members
            to share knowledge, resources, and experience — including licensing,
            strategy, and business operations.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <h2>Article II — Membership</h2>
        <h3>Section 1 — Eligibility</h3>
        <p>Membership is open to individuals and businesses who:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Operate an active or full-time business creating and selling templates,
            UI kits, component libraries, or design systems.
          </li>
          <li>Have a public track record of shipped, commercial products.</li>
          <li>
            Are willing to abide by this Charter and the Collective&apos;s Code
            of Conduct.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Section 2 — Admission</h3>
        <p>
          There are no dues or fees to join the Collective. To apply, contact any
          current member. Your application will be reviewed internally by the
          membership body. Admission decisions are based on eligibility,
          professional track record, and alignment with this Charter.
        </p>

        <h3>Section 3 — Good Standing</h3>
        <p>A member is in good standing when they:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Comply with this Charter and the Code of Conduct.</li>
          <li>
            Respond to membership votes and decisions within a reasonable
            timeframe.
          </li>
          <li>
            Engage in good faith to resolve concerns raised through the
            Collective&apos;s dispute resolution process (Article V).
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Section 4 — Loss of Good Standing</h3>
        <p>
          Loss of good standing may be determined by consensus of the membership
          body in cases of:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            A sustained pattern of behavior that conflicts with this Charter or
            the Code of Conduct.
          </li>
          <li>
            A refusal to engage constructively with the dispute resolution
            process.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Article III — Code of Conduct</h2>
        <h3>Section 1 — Ethical Practice</h3>
        <p>Members shall:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Respect the intellectual property of others — including code, designs,
            copy, and visual assets.
          </li>
          <li>
            Comply with all applicable copyright, trademark, and licensing laws.
          </li>
          <li>
            Comply with the licenses of open-source software and frameworks they
            use, and give appropriate attribution where required or customary.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Section 2 — Good Faith &amp; Professionalism</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            All discussions — especially around disputes, claims, or potential
            infringement — shall assume good faith.
          </li>
          <li>
            Present concerns professionally. Give others the benefit of the
            doubt.
          </li>
          <li>
            Focus on resolution and constructive outcomes, not public spectacle.
          </li>
          <li>
            Direct, private communication between parties should be the first step
            before escalation.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Section 3 — Solidarity Against Bad Actors</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            The Collective identifies and addresses patterns of harmful behavior
            in the industry — including serial copycats, license violators, and
            fraudulent operators.
          </li>
          <li>
            Members support each other in enforcing their rights, including
            coordinated public statements, shared legal resources, and platform
            reporting when warranted.
          </li>
          <li>
            Calling out bad actors is done with evidence, proportionality, and
            professionalism — never as a weapon for competitive advantage.
          </li>
          <li>
            For detailed guidance on evaluating copyright and infringement
            claims, see the{" "}
            <a href="/copyright-guide">Copyright Claims Guide</a>.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Article IV — Governance</h2>
        <h3>Section 1 — Structure</h3>
        <p>
          The Collective operates as a flat, consensus-driven body. As the
          membership grows, the Collective may elect:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            A <strong>Steward</strong> (or rotating Stewards) responsible for
            facilitating meetings, maintaining records, and managing the membership
            process.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Working Groups</strong> for specific initiatives (e.g., Legal
            Resources, Industry Standards).
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Section 2 — Decision-Making</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            Day-to-day decisions are made by open discussion and rough consensus.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Section 3 — Meetings</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            The Collective meets regularly (cadence to be determined by members)
            via virtual calls or async discussion threads.
          </li>
          <li>
            An annual review of this Charter is conducted to ensure it remains
            relevant.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Article V — Dispute Resolution</h2>
        <h3>Section 1 — Principles</h3>
        <p>
          All disputes — whether between members or involving external parties —
          shall be handled with good faith and proportionality. Details of any
          dispute shall be treated as confidential by all members until the
          Collective decides otherwise.
        </p>

        <h3>Section 2 — Between Members</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Private Resolution.</strong> Parties are expected to attempt
            direct, private resolution first. Most issues should be resolvable at
            this stage.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Facilitated Discussion.</strong> If private resolution fails,
            either party may request that a neutral member facilitate a
            conversation. The facilitator is selected by mutual agreement or, if
            needed, by the Steward.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Collective Review.</strong> If facilitated discussion does not
            resolve the matter, it may be brought before the membership body for
            review. The Collective will issue a formal recommendation that members
            are expected to honor as part of remaining in good standing.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          At any stage, if the complaint involves a direct competitor of the
          reporting member, the Collective shall take additional care to evaluate
          the claim on its merits, independent of competitive dynamics.
        </p>

        <h3>Section 3 — Against External Parties</h3>
        <p>
          Members retain full authority to enforce their rights independently
          against external parties. This includes issuing takedown requests,
          contacting platforms, sending cease-and-desist notices, and pursuing
          legal action at their own discretion. The Collective does not need to
          approve or be involved in individual enforcement.
        </p>
        <p>
          The Collective serves as a resource when a member needs advice,
          coordination, or collective weight behind an enforcement effort —
          particularly when individual action has been insufficient.
        </p>

        <h4>Requesting Collective Assistance</h4>
        <p>
          When a member seeks the Collective&apos;s involvement, they are expected
          to provide clear, professional documentation of the issue, including:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            A description of the alleged infringement or harmful behavior.
          </li>
          <li>
            Supporting evidence (screenshots, URLs, code comparisons, timestamps,
            or other relevant materials).
          </li>
          <li>
            A summary of any enforcement steps already taken and their outcomes.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Assessment &amp; Response</h4>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <strong>Review.</strong> The Collective reviews the documentation,
            applying the good-faith standard.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Action.</strong> The Collective decides on a proportional
            response, which may include:
            <ul>
              <li>Advice and guidance to the reporting member.</li>
              <li>A coordinated private communication to the external party.</li>
              <li>A coordinated public statement.</li>
              <li>
                Platform reporting on behalf of multiple affected members.
              </li>
              <li>Shared legal resources or legal referral.</li>
              <li>
                No collective action, if the evidence does not warrant it or the
                matter is better handled individually.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </DocWithToc>
    </Wrapper>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
